    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_83089584" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/83089584" />
    <a title="Sarah Magdalene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3100991-sarah-magdalene"><img alt="Sarah Magdalene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1262499081p2/3100991.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/83089584?book_show_action=true">Jan 02, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah Magdalene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah Magdalene" href="/user/show/3100991-sarah-magdalene">Sarah Magdalene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer83089584" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12752478619123563815">Suppose I could talk about &quot;The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love&quot;. But anything I said would just spoil it. Mishima deserves his mysteries kept for those interested enough to discover them personally. I will say that this story made think very deeply on the nature of love and spirituality. Human beings are such strange and perverse animals. They can spend a whole lifetime consciously trying to attain an abstract spiritual ideal only to throw it all away in an instant of futile passion. Desire</span>
  <span id="freeText12752478619123563815" style="display:none">Suppose I could talk about "The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love". But anything I said would just spoil it. Mishima deserves his mysteries kept for those interested enough to discover them personally. I will say that this story made think very deeply on the nature of love and spirituality. Human beings are such strange and perverse animals. They can spend a whole lifetime consciously trying to attain an abstract spiritual ideal only to throw it all away in an instant of futile passion. Desire for the unattainable is the one great constant, whether it be for Pure Land or for the ultimate expression of love. Even the desire not to desire is still desire. You cannot win.<br /><br />The whole collection (Death in Midsummer) is so carefully constructed that each story contributes to the overall theme and seems tied to the next in perfect fashion building of course to the climax of the Seppuku story and then fading away. This is the work of an uber mind, some one who considers every last detail of form and function many times over. Some one with an unparalleled knowledge and understanding of both his own culture and of ours, which is formidable combination to say the least. But much more than that, someone who genuinely feels very deeply and allows himself to be swept along by his passion. Love is his favourite subject in all his novels.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12752478619123563815" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


