    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_463058370" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/463058370" />
    <a title="Smiley " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2580971-smiley"><img alt="Smiley " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525349534p2/2580971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/463058370?book_show_action=true">Nov 25, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Smiley " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Smiley " href="/user/show/2580971-smiley">Smiley </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9784805306178" href="/book/show/15775442-death-in-midsummer-and-other-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=short-story">short-story</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer463058370" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4531239494562496155">I preferred the fourth story, &quot;The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love&quot;, which is interestingly imaginative, penetrative and contemplative since Mishima&apos;s narrative is so superb and brilliant that, I think, few could surpass or think as his equals. In fact, there are 10 stories in the contents but we are informed this is “a collection of nine of the finest stories” (back cover) and I wondered why such contradictory information should exist like that. So I hoped the staff of the publishing compan</span>
  <span id="freeText4531239494562496155" style="display:none">I preferred the fourth story, "The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love", which is interestingly imaginative, penetrative and contemplative since Mishima's narrative is so superb and brilliant that, I think, few could surpass or think as his equals. In fact, there are 10 stories in the contents but we are informed this is “a collection of nine of the finest stories” (back cover) and I wondered why such contradictory information should exist like that. So I hoped the staff of the publishing company would see to the matter in its next revised printing.<br /><br />This 16-page story aptly sets the scene by introducing the readers to a category of the ‘Pure Land’ that takes me back to reading some Buddhist-related texts. This sentence, “Furthermore, the smallest of these flowers has a diameter of two hundred and fifty yojanas.” (p. 61) instantly reminded me of a Thai word, that is, โยชน์ [Sanskrit : योजन (yojana) (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/yojana">https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/yojana</a>)]. This word implies literarily inestimable distance whenever we come across the word in Thai literature; however, if one needs to know its exact measurement, it is a distance of 5 miles or 8 kilometers [<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yojana">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yojana</a>]. <br /><br />Then, The Great Priest of Shiga Temple appears for the world to see and have pity on him due to his old age, we may wonder how old he is so he might be in his 70’s, 80’s or 90’s as evidenced from this sentence, “His eyebrows were white, and it was as much as he could do to move his old bones along as he hobbled on his stick from one part of the temple to another.” (p. 61) This has posted an abhorring figure most people don’t want to see or even meet him. In fact, being in an unimaginatively-advanced old age is not his fault or sin, he simply has a good long life towards his ripe old age few could dream or think to be like him. <br /><br />Next, one spring evening while performing the rite of Water Contemplation by the lake, the priest dictated by fate unintentionally happens to see the Great Imperial Concubine in her carriage stopping nearby. The following excerpt is, I think, the first climax leading to his indescribable torment and suffering:<br /><br /> Unwittingly the Great Priest glanced in her direction and at once he was overwhelmed by her beauty. His eyes met hers and, as he did nothing to avert his gaze, she did not take it upon herself to turn away. It was not that her liberality of spirit was such as to allow men to gaze on her with brazen looks; but the motives of this austere old ascetic could hardly, she felt, be those of ordinary men. (p. 63)<br /><br />And the following devastating effect, “In the twinkling of an eye the present world had wreaked its revenge on the priest with terrible force. What he had imagined to be completely safe had collapsed in ruins.” (p. 63)<br /><br />Over time, the priest unavoidably suffers, in which I would like my friends to read by yourselves. Moreover, this phase is equally interesting:<br /><br />	The Great Priest of Shiga Temple was fighting. In the fight that he had waged against the flesh in his youth he had always been buoyed up by the hope of inheriting the future world. But this desperate fight of his old age was linked with a sense of irreparable loss. (p. 68)<br /><br />Finally, he can make it by going to the residence of the Great Imperial Concubine amidst her fear due to his undaunted willingness in keeping waiting to meet her just once in his life. And this is how she contemplates as her response:<br /><br />	The Great Imperial Concubine of Kyogoku felt a strange cold hand touching her hand. At the same time she was aware of a warm moisture. Her hand was being bedewed by someone else’s tears. Yet when the pallid shafts of morning light began to reach her through the blind, the lady's fervent faith imbued her with a wonderful inspiration: she became convinced that the unknown hand which touched hers belonged to none other than the Buddha. (p. 74)<br /><br />I think she deserves to be an angel-like heroine for her noble mind. We can’t help agreeing with Mishima’s fantastic descriptive allowing both parties to stay and live in peace since, not long after that incident, they part forever. Especially the last five paragraphs, they’re blissfully, beautifully written to the extent that I’d like to invite my friends to read and enjoy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4531239494562496155" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


