<div id="review_1281944318" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1281944318" />
    <a title="Greg Brozeit" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26552534-greg-brozeit"><img alt="Greg Brozeit" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544324486p2/26552534.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1281944318?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg Brozeit" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg Brozeit" href="/user/show/26552534-greg-brozeit">Greg Brozeit</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26552534-greg-brozeit?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1281944318" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7341186251618385185">A haunting sense of sadness and tragedy pervades Mishima’s writing. This collection of nine short stories and one short play focuses on themes of loss, death, honor, superstition, jealousy, motives, and piety. Although I am woefully ignorant of Japanese history and culture, I feel that these stories are somehow intense primers, or insights, to a world it would otherwise take me much longer to appreciate and comprehend.<br/><br/>I read the story “Patriotism” quite coincidentally on the 4th of July. But it </span>
  <span id="freeText7341186251618385185" style="display:none">A haunting sense of sadness and tragedy pervades Mishima’s writing. This collection of nine short stories and one short play focuses on themes of loss, death, honor, superstition, jealousy, motives, and piety. Although I am woefully ignorant of Japanese history and culture, I feel that these stories are somehow intense primers, or insights, to a world it would otherwise take me much longer to appreciate and comprehend.<br /><br />I read the story “Patriotism” quite coincidentally on the 4th of July. But it is very different from the shallow jingoism that normally defines American celebrations. Mishima’s story about a young couple’s personal, violent response to a military mutiny is about devotion to honor and fidelity. <br /><br />“Onnagata” refers to a feminine actor who plays female roles in kabuki plays. As Mishima writes, "An onnagata is the child born of the illicit union between dream and reality." As the lives of the three main characters intertwine, their interaction is a kabuki of sorts that plays itself out through misunderstandings and manipulation.<br /><br />My only regret is that I had to read these in translation. Mishima was a writer of great intensity who could elevate minute details to profound events.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7341186251618385185" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

