<div id="review_1649311118" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1649311118" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1649311118?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=yukio-mishima">yukio-mishima</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=japanese-fiction">japanese-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1649311118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14347655318014394267">My first foray into Mishima&apos;s short stories after having read most of his novels. A few were a bit inscrutable-- the one about kabuki actors, I&apos;m clearly missing most of the picture given my lack of education in this area-- but others were fantastic. I couldn&apos;t help but grit my teeth through the sepukku passages in &quot;Patriotism,&quot; and what could be more jarring than the whole of &quot;The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love,&quot; with its vaguely Temple-of-the-Golden-Pavilion story of Buddhism clashing har</span>
  <span id="freeText14347655318014394267" style="display:none">My first foray into Mishima's short stories after having read most of his novels. A few were a bit inscrutable-- the one about kabuki actors, I'm clearly missing most of the picture given my lack of education in this area-- but others were fantastic. I couldn't help but grit my teeth through the sepukku passages in "Patriotism," and what could be more jarring than the whole of "The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love," with its vaguely Temple-of-the-Golden-Pavilion story of Buddhism clashing hard with materiality. In fact, these two stories might be the perfect gateway drug for Mishima. The whole collection is worth reading, but these two are essentials.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14347655318014394267" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


