<div id="review_2692055954" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2692055954" />
    <a title="Lauren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25223589-lauren"><img alt="Lauren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614984527p2/25223589.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2692055954?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren" href="/user/show/25223589-lauren">Lauren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140084283" href="/book/show/1818416.Death_In_Midsummer_And_Other_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25223589-lauren?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2692055954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8150669976286014984">In the short story &quot;Onnagata,&quot; included in this collection, Mishima writes, &quot;an onnagata is the child born of the illicit union between dream and reality.&quot; I think this description could easily be applied to himself.<br/><br/>If I had to read one author for the rest of my life, I guess I&apos;d choose Mishima. This guy is impossibly talented. Every story of his leaves an impression on the reader that&apos;s both sublime, nostalgic, and a little upsetting, like when you pass a stranger wearing the perfume an old lov</span>
  <span id="freeText8150669976286014984" style="display:none">In the short story "Onnagata," included in this collection, Mishima writes, "an onnagata is the child born of the illicit union between dream and reality." I think this description could easily be applied to himself.<br /><br />If I had to read one author for the rest of my life, I guess I'd choose Mishima. This guy is impossibly talented. Every story of his leaves an impression on the reader that's both sublime, nostalgic, and a little upsetting, like when you pass a stranger wearing the perfume an old lover once wore. His writing is about as sensationally-fulfilling, too. It's so decadent and rich, each character fleshed out no matter how short of an appearance they have. Nothing comes off as forced or unnatural, regardless of the Romantic context that could never fall in place of reality. Mix that in with his insane, dramatic personal life and he makes some sort of tragic czar of prose. If his translated work blows me away this much, I can't imagine how moving and important his original work is. <br /><br />But I can't read Japanese.<br /><br />Pick this up if you get the chance, especially for the following stories:<br />PATRIOTISM<br />ONNAGATA<br />THE PRIEST OF SHIGA TEMPLE AND HIS LOVE<br />DOJOJI</span>
  <a data-text-id="8150669976286014984" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


