<div id="review_831874788" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/831874788" />
    <a title="Booze Hound" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3079518-booze-hound"><img alt="Booze Hound" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607625452p2/3079518.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/831874788?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Booze Hound" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Booze Hound" href="/user/show/3079518-booze-hound">Booze Hound</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer831874788" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18323049291406521716">This guy has the dark side of humankind down. He knows what it is to be human and experience pain (or so it seems). Grieving, death, decay, truthful and raw emotion, etc. I hate to compare him to Hemingway (I have heard this comparison before, I am totally unoriginal and am stealing that comparison), but he is like a dark, brutal, more emotional Hemingway...From Japan! It seems his stories always have a snap at the end that the rest of the story leads up to. I can&apos;t think of a better example of </span>
  <span id="freeText18323049291406521716" style="display:none">This guy has the dark side of humankind down. He knows what it is to be human and experience pain (or so it seems). Grieving, death, decay, truthful and raw emotion, etc. I hate to compare him to Hemingway (I have heard this comparison before, I am totally unoriginal and am stealing that comparison), but he is like a dark, brutal, more emotional Hemingway...From Japan! It seems his stories always have a snap at the end that the rest of the story leads up to. I can't think of a better example of Freytag's Pyramid (don't worry, I am not that smart, had to look that up; it just came to mind when reading Mishima's stuff). It might just be this one short story, but it had the similar style as "Patriotism". The climax often involving the climax of emotions, violence, feelings, and the writing is of course the best in these pages of the climax. The man is a genius for sure and a highly underrated writer.<br /><br />Short Stories:<br /><br />Death in Midsummer (Grieving loss of loved ones)<br /><br />"One day she pricked her finger, and a drop of blood oozed out. She was frightened. Pain was associated with death."<br /><br />"The tragedy left them as a castaway leaves a sinking ship."<br /><br />There are some other unusual quotes (I was lazy and didnt put them in immediately, now I can't find them and don't care...neither should you) These quotes consist of burst of awkward pleasure, when seeing a child she hopes the child dies. Real interesting stuff going on here and no holding back for Mishima as far as what it is for a human to go through the grieving process of a death.<br /><br /><br />One Million Yen<br /><br />I dont know what the hell was going on in that story...minus one star...boo...<br /><br />Thermos Bottles<br /><br />What is with napes and white skin?! Japanese people are weirdos...Anyways, the story would be easier to follow if they changed the Japanese names with Western names like 'Bill' and 'Sally'. It can be all too confusing and I demand they change the literature to fit my Western-centric opinion!! Anyways, the way he describes people is so psychologically precise, it can be frightening. Genius.<br /><br />There was some other stories that were mediocre and worth not really writing about...However, they probably werent that mediocre and I am just lazy...<br /><br />Onnagata<br /><br />"His long, straight hair hung down so far- to the tip of his nose- that he was frequently obliged to push it back. Masuyama was rather disappointed by his first impression. He had supposed that a man who had been singled out for his abilities would have attempted to distinguish himself somehow from the stereotype of society, but this man dressed and acted exactly in the way one would expect of the typical young man of the modern theatre."<br /><br />"He felt as though a big, black, wet umbrella were being noisily opened inside his heart...But Masuyama knew that along with disillusion a new sensation was assaulting him, jealousy. He dreaded where this new emotion might lead him."<br /><br />The Pearl<br /><br />Ugh, middle aged women bickering over some pearl. If I want to hear bickering and drama among middle aged women I can attend a family gathering with my mother and middle aged aunts... Come on!<br /><br />This book took a nose dive; started out amazing with Death in Midsummer and slowly got worse and worse with each story. Goddamnit!! Disappointed me Mishima! You have brought shame! <br /><br /><br />Swaddling Clothes<br /><br />"No doubt Toshiko derived a certain satisfaction from her somber thoughts..."<br /><br /><br />OK, this story saved it...You are lucky this time Mishima, but next will be another story...`</span>
  <a data-text-id="18323049291406521716" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


