        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer47318559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9612750467087265297"><i>Death in Midsummer and Other Stories</i> is a wonderful collection of some of Mishima Yukio&apos;s finest short stories. His supreme command of language, in-depth understanding of human nature, and skill in covering a diverse range of subject matter is remarkable. He is without peer in Japan and the most versatile writer since the Meiji period.<br/><br/>Among the stories in this collection, the most complex and esoteric is <i>The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love</i>. Mishima beautifully recreates a dream-like landscap</span>
  <span id="freeText9612750467087265297" style="display:none"><i>Death in Midsummer and Other Stories</i> is a wonderful collection of some of Mishima Yukio's finest short stories. His supreme command of language, in-depth understanding of human nature, and skill in covering a diverse range of subject matter is remarkable. He is without peer in Japan and the most versatile writer since the Meiji period.<br /><br />Among the stories in this collection, the most complex and esoteric is <i>The Priest of Shiga Temple and His Love</i>. Mishima beautifully recreates a dream-like landscape through the juxtaposition of an ethereal and blissful world, with a hellish world of darkness and gloom. One is immediately reminded of <i>The Garden of Earthly Delights</i> by Hieronymus Bosch or Dante Alighieri's <i>Divine Comedy</i>, both world masterpieces. The story is strangely inspiring and a unique glimpse into the mind and soul of an exceptional writer and thinker.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9612750467087265297" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

